(307, 'Dwarf Japanese Maple \'Shishi yatsubusa\' Acer palmatum Live Grafted Tree Layered Slightly Cupped Leaves---Hard To Find!!', 'dwarf-japanese-maple-shishi-yatsubusa-acer-palmatum-live-grafted-tree-layered-slightly-cupped-leaves-hard-to-find', 'ETSY-0035', 'simple', 14, NULL, 'Japanese Maples', 32.95, NULL, 19.77, NULL, 'https://i.etsystatic.com/20088520/r/il/01d3a0/7042722670/il_fullxfull.7042722670_rg82.jpg', 'WE CANNOT SHIP TO THE FOLLOWING STATES DUE TO SHIPPING RESTRICTIONS: CALIFORNIA, OREGON, WASHINGTON, ARIZONA, ALASKA, HAWAII, IDAHO AND NEVADA\n**WE CANNOT SHIP TO P.O. BOXES!!**\nSECOND PICTURE IS A REPRESENTATION OF THE PLANT YOU WILL RECEIVE.\n***ITEMS ARE TAPED IN THE BOX FOR SECURE SHIPPING. PLEASE BE CAREFUL TO REMOVE TAPE FIRST BEFORE REMOVING PLANT(S)***\n\nThis listing is for 1 plant that is 10\"- 12\" tall. This grafted dwarf cultivar is highly sought after and hard to find!! What makes it so special is the way the leaves grow!! The name itself gives away its character: \"Yatsubusa\" translates to \"dwarf\" or \"eight tassels,\" referencing its highly congested, compact growth habit, while \"Shishi\" means \"lion,\" hinting at its rumpled, texture-heavy appearance.\nBonsai: It is a legendary choice among bonsai enthusiasts because its leaf size and internodes (the space between leaf joints) are naturally small.\nContainer Gardening: It thrives in pots on patios or courtyards where its unique texture can be admired up close.\nSmall Landscapes: Perfect for rock gardens, small urban spaces, or as a focal point near a prominent entryway.\n\nGrowth Habit & Size: It features an incredibly dense, multi-branched structure. Growth is slow, typically averaging just 2 to 4 inches per year. Over 10 to 15 years, it will mature into a compact shrub-like tree reaching about 4 to 6 feet tall and wide.\n\nFoliage Texture: The leaves are tiny, sharply lobed, and grow very close together along the twigs. This tight clustering creates a highly unique, deeply layered \"ruffled\" texture that looks almost like a natural bonsai even without pruning.\n\nSeasonal Colors:\nSpring: Emerges a bright, vibrant green, sometimes with faint reddish margins on the new tips.\nSummer: Settles into a rich, deep emerald green that holds up remarkably well without scorching if given proper care.\nAutumn: Transforms into a brilliant display of orange and crimson red.\n\nSunlight: Thrives in filtered sun or morning sun with afternoon shade. While it is more sun-tolerant than some delicate, variegated maples, hot afternoon sun in warmer climates can stress the compact foliage.\nSoil: Requires moist, rich, organic soil that drains flawlessly. Japanese maples hate \"wet feet,\" which can quickly cause root rot.\n\nCommon Name: \'Shishi yatsubusa\' Japanese Maple\nBotanical Name: Acer palmatum\nHardiness Zones: 5 - 9\nBloom Time: N/A\nSunlight: Full sun/part sun\nSoil Requirements: Moist, well drained soil\nMature Size: 4\' to 6\' tall and wide\nBloom Color: N/A\nDeciduous or Evergreen: Deciduous', '1 plant that is 10\"- 12\" tall.', '[\"Japanese Maples\",\"Easy To Grow\",\"Low Maintenance\",\"Dwarf Tree\",\"Rare Tree\",\"Ornamental Tree\",\"Fairy Garden\",\"Rock Garden\",\"Small Garden Spaces\",\"Container Garden\",\"Unique Leaves\",\"Dramatic Fall Color\",\"Layered Leaves\"]', 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 1, 5, 1, 0, 5, '2026-06-24 16:09:06', '2026-06-24 16:09:06'),
